snippet.textDisplay:
I loved you
There was a time that I loved you
Even though destiny didn't want me to do it I loved you
In the silence I loved you
In the loneliness I loved you
In the darkness of the night I loved you
With both hands tied I loved you
Behind the door while I was sobbing I loved you
When my heart couldn't take it anymore I loved you
When I talked and told everything to God I loved you
Against everybody I loved you
Against myself I loved you
Against absolutely everything I loved you
And when life conceded me a respite I loved you
With the force of the wind...
With the fury of a hurricane...
With the power of the storm...
With the tenderness that was born from the deepest...
With the passion that consumed me...
With all my soul and being I loved you
And again, against the will of destiny I loved you
When that unburied treasure began to shine again I loved you
When I dreamt and was already disposing my very life in your hands I loved you
Finally, the effort was in vain and despite all that I loved you
I went all the way and at the end of it I loved you
Not even yourself can know how much I really loved you
Now, always alone and resigned, it is clear to me that I loved you
Now your presence only means the memory of your face, your voice, your smell, your skin...
I loved you...
I always loved you

I think of you when it rains.
I always think of you when it rains.
It's funny to think that rain has always been there, marking our history. That day I offered you my coat, but what I was really offering you was my life. The rain, you soaked and cold, your smile as you deny it, it never leaves my mind that I should have voted and made you accept the coat anyway.
The rain was always there.
I think of you when it rains, like that day when I asked you out and the world collapsed into water. I was so afraid you'd give up, but there we were and the rain.
I don't know what it means, but the day you left me it wasn't raining outside, there weren't even clouds, but inside me, a storm ran from my heart to my eyes, forming a salty and painful rain, not the same as always. .
Today when you told me that there is another person kissing your mouth, touching your body, I rained all over inside, a cold and silent rain, the kind that certainly kills a part of whoever lets themselves get wet by it. This time it didn't overflow in your eyes, I couldn't, I couldn't let you get wet in it, I couldn't let your heart notice, so in the landscape of my face I hid the drizzle inside me.
Before the day ended, small rays of sun fought against the wind and rain inside me, when outside once again the old rain fell again.
I think of you when it rains, but unfortunately it has rained so much on me, I am flooded and I don't know what to do, I am drowning in myself, because I don't know how to swim and I can't hide from the cold storm that has taken over. I hope to return to that rain that has always been our sign, the one that falls outside while desire, love, affection burns inside us.
I think of you when it rains, please let's get wet in the rain together again, but let our chest be summer.

The young lady, no more than twenty, stood in the midst of a violent rainstorm, with nothing but a thin coat to protect her from the elements. The sheet of paper in her hand was damp, but she held it firmly anyway, as if it was the only thing keeping her anchored to the world. She raised her face to the sky, as if hoping to find some answers up there. Her eyes were red and swollen from crying, and her nose was running. Her once-beautiful curls were now disheveled and matted, sticking to her face. A black streak of mascara ran down both cheeks, and her lips were trembling.

She began to scream, a high-pitched sound that was lost in the roar of the rain. Her scream was a mix of anger, despair, and pain, and it seemed to have no end. People passing by on the street gave her curious looks, but they kept walking, not wanting to get involved. Her screaming continued, her voice getting hoarser and more ragged, but she didn't stop. She was lost in her world of pain and confusion, and the only way she knew how to express it was through her screams.

Finally, she collapsed on the wet pavement. Her body was shaking, and she was gasping for air. She lay there, her eyes closed, the rain pelting against her face. The letter was still clutched tightly in her hand, smudged and unreadable. The rain was a fitting end to this sad scene, a reminder that some things in life are beyond our control.

-The rainy day
